{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6f36f1ea-116b-45e7-8f55-9331d6697745","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Recursive wildcard glob (line 9 of `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThe `**\\*.*` pattern forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This is expensive at scale and re-evaluated on every design-time build in IDEs.\n\n## 2. File I/O via property function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during evaluation blocks the evaluator on disk I/O. Property functions run synchronously and defeat evaluation caching.\n\n## 3. Deeply chained imports (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds an XML parse + evaluation pass. While 3 levels is modest, this pattern tends to grow over time and compounds with the issues above since every import re-scopes property/item evaluation.\n\n### Recommendations\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| Recursive glob | Replace with explicit file list or narrow the pattern (e.g., `*.json` in a known folder) |\n| `ReadAllText` in evaluation | Move to a target (runs at build time, not evaluation time) or use a response file |\n| Import chain | Flatten into fewer files; merge properties that don't need isolation |\n\nThe **biggest offenders** are #1 and #2—they introduce I/O during evaluation, which is supposed to be fast and cacheable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"103e8d1a-7c45-4957-aa64-2208e3024296","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.","outputTokens":452,"requestId":"5C4F:354610:64540D5:6D5953F:69F15DCE"},"id":"bf7a5f91-d747-40d4-b255-bd509b7b64ed","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:24:43.833Z","parentId":"5449a060-6932-47f9-8552-32680c9994f8"}
